1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,570
In 1936, Mr. Barrymore broke his hip.

2
00:00:03,600 --> 00:00:05,570
The fracture never healed.

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:10,770
Most people thought Mr. Barrymore was finished, but not Mr. Barrymore.

4
00:00:10,880 --> 00:00:15,730
He used the setback to pave the way to even greater acting success.

5
00:00:15,920 --> 00:00:23,890
For the next 18 years, despite pain that never abated, he played dozens of successful roles in a wheelchair.

6
00:00:24,720 --> 00:00:31,649
On March 15, 1945, W. Colvin Williams was walking behind a tank in France.

7
00:00:31,840 --> 00:00:37,250
The tank hit a mine, exploded, and permanently blinded Mr. Williams.

8
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:43,330
But this didn't stop Mr. Williams from pursuing his goal to be a minister and counselor.

9
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:53,169
When he was graduated from college, and with honors, too, Mr. Williams said he thought his blindness will actually be an asset in my career.

10
00:00:53,520 --> 00:00:55,809
I can never judge by appearances.

11
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,490
Therefore, I can always give a person a second chance.

12
00:00:59,840 --> 00:01:05,409
My blindness keeps me from cutting myself off from a person because of the way he looks.

13
00:01:05,760 --> 00:01:11,890
I want to be the kind of person to whom anyone can come and feel secure to express himself.

14
00:01:12,640 --> 00:01:19,250
Isn't that a magnificent living example of cruel bitter defeat being turned into victory?

15
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:23,649
Defeat is only a state of mind and nothing more.

16
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:29,649
One of my friends, who is a substantial and successful investor in the stock market,

17
00:01:29,920 --> 00:01:35,010
carefully appraises each investment decision in the light of his past experiences.

18
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:42,850
One time, he told me, when I first started investing 15 years ago, I really got singed a few times.

19
00:01:43,040 --> 00:01:46,450
Like most amateurs, I wanted to get rich quick.

20
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:48,610
Instead, I got broke quick.

21
00:01:48,720 --> 00:01:50,289
But that didn't stop me.

22
00:01:50,560 --> 00:01:54,850
I knew the basic strengths of the economy, and that over the long pull,

23
00:01:54,960 --> 00:01:59,409
well-selected stocks are about the best investment anybody can make.

24
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:06,690
So I just regarded those first bad investments as part of the cost of my education," he laughed.

25
00:02:07,440 --> 00:02:13,330
On the other hand, I know a number of people who, having made an unwise investment or two,

26
00:02:13,440 --> 00:02:15,970
are strictly anti-securities.

27
00:02:16,320 --> 00:02:26,289
Rather than analyze their mistakes and join in a good thing, they reach the completely false conclusion that investing in common stocks is just a form of gambling,

28
00:02:26,289 --> 00:02:29,090
and sooner or later everybody loses.

29
00:02:30,080 --> 00:02:34,049
Decide right now to salvage something from every setback.

30
00:02:34,240 --> 00:02:37,809
Next time things seem to go wrong on the job or at home,

31
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:41,250
calm down and find out what caused the trouble.
